properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Yarra River to Millgrove.

The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 21 mm in the upper part of the catchment and about 9 mm in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Friday 28 October 2022. Rainfall totals of 5-15 mm are forecast for the catchment for Saturday 29 October 2022.

Yarra River to Millgrove:
The level of the Yarra River at Millgrove is currently steady at 2.04 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (2.00 metres). It is expected to drop below the Minor Flood Level on Saturday evening (29 October 2022).

Minor to Moderate flooding in the Yarra/Watts River catchment is causing substantial inundation in the rural and/or urban areas, and disruption to traffic. Melba Highway at Yarra Glen is expected to get flooded.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • Minor flooding in the Yarra/Watts River catchment is affecting low-lying areas adjacent to the waterway including bicycle paths.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 09:30 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This is a Final Minor Flood Warning for Mt Emu Creek Skipton. 

MINOR FLOODING HAS EASED ALONG THE MT EMU CREEK AT SKIPTON   

  • The Mt Emu Creek at Skipton peaked around the minor flood level during Friday evening and river levels are now falling.   No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Saturday and into Sunday.     
  •  Forecast rainfall from Sunday afternoon and into early next week may cause renewed river level rises and areas of minor flooding. The situation is being closely monitored, and further flood warnings will be issued if necessary.
  • The Mt Emu Creek at Skipton is currently at 3.72 metres and falling, below the minor flood level.
The threat of flooding is reduced. Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and beware of hazards remaining in the warning area.
What you should do:

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

If your home or business has been flooded:
  • Check for building damage before you enter.
  • Have all electrical and gas equipment professionally tested before use.
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible.

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Damage to roads and buildings caused by flooding may still exist in your area. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This will be the last warning for this flood. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:

  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.location: Broken River Benalla to Casey Weir
properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Broken River Benalla to Case Weir.

Catchments in the flood watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall. 

Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the watch area from Monday afternoon. Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible from early next week at some locations. 

The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.   

If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT!    

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall. 

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do:
  • Check out the Benalla Local Flood Guide and/or the Rural City of Benalla Flood Emergency Plan. For more detailed information and flood maps, etc, go to https://www.ses.vic.gov.au/plan-and-stay-safe/flood-guides/benalla-rural-city-council
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

properties.location: Avoca River downstream of Charlton Town
properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Avoca River downstream of Charlton.

Minor flooding has eased at Downstream Charlton Town. Minor flooding is slowly rising at Quambatook.

  • The Avoca River at Quambatook is currently at 2.17 metres and slowly rising, with minor flooding.
  • The Avoca River at Quambatook is likely to peak around the moderate flood level (2.20 m) during Saturday.
  • The river level is expected to remain above the minor flood level (2.00 m) during Saturday and into Sunday.
In the 24 hours to 12pm Saturday, rainfall totals of less than 5mm were recorded in the Avoca River catchment. No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Saturday. Further rainfall is forecast from late Sunday which may lead to renewed rises.

The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Mosquito alert:
The risk of mosquito breeding is high. You can reduce your risk of being bitten and getting sick:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.
  • Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Check the VicTraffic website for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River Biggara to Bringenbrong.

Minor flooding is occurring at Khancoban Pondage and Bringenbrong. Minor flooding is possible at Jingelic Saturday evening.

Minor flooding is occurring along the Swampy Plains River at Khancoban Pondage and along the Murray River at Bringenbrong. Minor flooding may develop at Jingellic during Saturday evening, with a peak around the minor flood level possible overnight Saturday into Sunday.

Snowy Hydro advise that the releases from Khancoban Pondage are continuing above the minor flood level during Saturday.

Murray River Biggara to Bringenbrong

  • The river level is currently at 3.13 metres and falling, with minor flooding. It is likely to remain above the minor flood level (3.00 m) during Saturday and into Sunday.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Campaspe Barnadown to Rochester.

Information relevant to Rochester Township will be issued within this message for Barnadown to Rochester. The separate Rochester Township advice message will no longer be issued. 

  • Moderate flooding is continuing along the Campaspe River at Echuca. 
  • In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Saturday, rainfall totals of up to 10 mm have been recorded in the Campaspe River catchment. 
  • Showers are forecast for the next few days. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary

The latest community newsletter from Saturday 29 October is available here: Community newsletter
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • You may see animals attempting to move to higher ground, including snakes.
  • Leave all uninjured wildlife alone and they are likely to be fatigued and stressed.
  • If you see animals that appear to e injured or caught in floodwater, call 136 186 or advise via the wildlife emergency app.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 11:00 am or as the situation changes.

Mosquito Alert    
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease
What you can do:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing.  
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin. 
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens. 
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 

Flood Recovery Hotline - Call 1800 560 760
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with:
  • navigating available supports
  • clean-up
  • temporary accommodation
  • mental health and wellbeing support
The recovery hotline is open from 7.30am-7.30pm everyday.
Need an interpreter? Call the hotline on 1800 560 760 and press 9.
For flood and storm information and support in NSW visit nsw.gov.au/floods
If you require assistance relating to insurance matters, please call the Insurance Council Australia's disaster hotline on 1800 734 621.

  • If your buildings have been impacted by flood waters you should have your property inspected by a registered electrician. Visit the Energy Safe Victoria site for more: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/energy-safety-during-floods/
  • For more information on any assistance you need, visit emergency.vic.gov.au/relief/#relief_assistance
Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.location: Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal
properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal.

Updated Community information: Please find here the YouTube link for the Community Update from the Cobram community meeting recorded Saturday and is still relevant over the next few days.  To watch the link to Community Update on YouTube click on or follow this link: https://youtu.be/rJqfiT3yCC4

Flood operations are being conducted by the Murray-Darling Basin Authority (MDBA) at Hume Dam to manage inflows from the upper Murray, Mitta Mitta River and other tributaries. MDBA are working closely with the Bureau and WaterNSW to plan release strategies.

As at 1700hrs today, 41,880ML/Day is being released from Hume Dam.

Further rainfall is forecast during Monday and Tuesday, which may cause renewed river level rises and flooding. The situation is being closely monitored and revised predictions will be provided if necessary.

The situation is being closely monitored and revised predictions will be provided if necessary.

Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal:
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Murray River at Albury and possible at Yarrawonga. Moderate flooding is occurring at Corowa and possible at Tocumwal.
  • The Murray River at Albury may reach around 4.60 metres during Sunday, with minor flooding.
  • The Murray River at Corowa may reach around 6.20 metres during Monday, with moderate flooding.
  • The Murray River at Yarrawonga Downstream may reach the minor flood level (6.40 metres) during Monday.
  • The Murray River at Tocumwal is likely to exceed the minor flood level (6.40 metres) late Saturday. The river level may reach the moderate flood level (6.70 metres) during Tuesday.

NSW SES Declaration of Emergency Area 
The NSW State Emergency Service have declared the following areas of the Murray River are an emergency area under the State Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act):
  • Downstream of Tocumwal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge. 
  •  Murray River from the Tocumwal Road Bridge to Tooleybuc Bridge 
Under section 22 of the SES Act people are directed as follows: 
  • Leave the emergency area. 
  • Do not enter the emergency area. 
This applies to all commercial and recreational users of the rivers. No boats can enter the emergency area and people cannot enter the area for any recreational purpose such as fishing or swimming.

Updated Community Information: 
In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.    
Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  
Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning. If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.    

If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT!    

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall.  

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 05:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • For road closure information go to www.traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au or phone 13 11 70.
  • For health information and support contact the below organisations: Lifeline on www.lifeline.org.au or phone 13 11 14. Beyond Blue on www.beyondblue.org.au or phone 1300 224 636. Kids Helpine on www.kidshelp.com.au or phone 1800 551 800. SANE Australia on www.sane.org or phone 1800 187 263.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.  

Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home. Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  •  Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  •  Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  •  Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  •  Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick.
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal.
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away - including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.
Recovery:
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  • Register for clean up on private property; 
  • Navigating financial and other support;
  • Access to temporary accommodation;
  • Mental health and wellbeing support.

The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit www.erv.vic.gov.au for further information. 

For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. 
For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077. 

This is a community message to advise the community not to build own levees as it changes the flow of the water and impacting other properties.
properties.text: ADVICE - RIVERINE FLOOD - Stay Informed Incident Location: Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal Issue Date: Saturday 29 October 2022, 05:27 pm Next Update: Sunday 30 October 2022, 05:30 pm More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/25454/moreinfo This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal. Updated Community information: Please find here the YouTube link for the Community Update from the Cobram community meeting recorded Saturday and is still relevant over the next few days. To watch the link to Community Update on YouTube click on or follow this link: https://youtu.be/rJqfiT3yCC4 Flood operations are being conducted by the Murray-Darling Basin Authority (MDBA) at Hume Dam to manage inflows from the upper Murray, Mitta Mitta River and other tributaries. MDBA are working closely with the Bureau and WaterNSW to plan release strategies. As at 1700hrs today, 41,880ML/Day is being released from Hume Dam. Further rainfall is forecast during Monday and Tuesday, which may cause renewed river level rises and flooding. The situation is being closely monitored and revised predictions will be provided if necessary. The situation is being closely monitored and revised predictions will be provided if necessary. Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal: - Minor flooding is occurring along the Murray River at Albury and possible at Yarrawonga. Moderate flooding is occurring at Corowa and possible at Tocumwal. - The Murray River at Albury may reach around 4.60 metres during Sunday, with minor flooding. - The Murray River at Corowa may reach around 6.20 metres during Monday, with moderate flooding. - The Murray River at Yarrawonga Downstream may reach the minor flood level (6.40 metres) during Monday. - The Murray River at Tocumwal is likely to exceed the minor flood level (6.40 metres) late Saturday. The river level may reach the moderate flood level (6.70 metres) during Tuesday. NSW SES Declaration of Emergency Area The NSW State Emergency Service have declared the following areas of the Murray River are an emergency area under the State Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act): - Downstream of Tocumwal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge. - Murray River from the Tocumwal Road Bridge to Tooleybuc Bridge Under section 22 of the SES Act people are directed as follows: - Leave the emergency area. - Do not enter the emergency area. This applies to all commercial and recreational users of the rivers. No boats can enter the emergency area and people cannot enter the area for any recreational purpose such as fishing or swimming. Updated Community Information: In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick. To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water. Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home. Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning. If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly. Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree. If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT! Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall. Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater. In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is for Barmah and Lower Moira .
  • An evacuation warning remains current. It is still not safe to return. Continue to avoid flood-affected areas.
  • Dangerous floodwater and widespread and significantly contaminated floodwater remain in several parts of the town.

  • In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   
  • To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas.   

  • The Picola to Barmah Road is now open, however shallow water may still covers some parts of the road.
  • The Nathalia relief centre is still open at the Nathalia Community Centre,42 Robinson St, Nathalia.
It is not safe for people to return to Barmah and parts of Lower Moira.   
If you have not evacuated, you should now shelter in the highest location possible.
What you should do:

  • Be aware of the increased likelihood of trees falling due to the very wet ground, especially in windy conditions. Never shelter under trees.  

If you have not already evacuated:
  • Stay where you are and shelter in the highest location possible.
  • Be aware that you may be isolated by floodwater for a significant amount of time.
  • Check you have enough food, drinking water and medications - if you do not, phone Triple Zero (000) for assistance.
If you have already evacuated:
  • Do not return to your home until a Safe to Return notification is issued.
  • Register at a relief centre so that your friends, family and authorities can be informed that you are safe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

This evacuation warning will remain in place until the area is declared safe to return.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flood levels may remain above floor level of a single-storey home.
  • Based on historic data, this flood has had a similar impact as the 1993 flood.
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victor
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 31/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Wharparilla area.. 

Flooding has impacted residents in the area of Glyn Road, Wharparilla. 

Flooding is expected to remain at current levels for the next week.

The latest community newsletter from Saturday 29 October is available here: Community newsletter
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 
Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • A small number of properties are likely to be impacted in or around Glyn Road Wharparilla.
  • Roads around the Glyn Road Wharparilla area may be be impacted.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the King River.

Moderate Flooding continuing at Docker Road Bridge.

Moderate flooding is occurring along the King River at Docker Rd Bridge and has extended downstream to Wangaratta during Saturday afternoon. Minor flooding is occurring along the King River at Downstream Lake William Hovell.

No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Saturday and into Sunday.

Forecast rainfall from Sunday evening and for the first few days of next week is likely to see renewed rises throughout the Ovens and King catchments. 

King River
  • The King River downstream of Lake William Hovell is currently at 1.96 metres and steady, with minor flooding. It is likely to remain above the minor flood level (1.80 m) during Saturday and into Sunday.
  • The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is currently peaking around 4.05 metres, with moderate flooding. It is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (3.95 m) overnight Saturday into Sunday.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
The Emergency Warning to Evacuate, following flooding at Kerang has been lifted and it is safe for people who live in this area to return.

Water levels are falling at the Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge and are expected to continue falling, remaining above the minor flood level for the next few days.

  • Tourists and people from neighbouring communities are advised that access to and from Kerang is limited. Only residents who previously evacuated are advised to return at this time.
  • Dangerous flood water continues to significantly impact Kerang and surrounding areas.
  • Although the river has peaked, with some levees still overtopped in sections, many areas are experiencing significant flooding and emergency services continue efforts towards sandbagging and asset protection.
  • Emergency services and Gannawarra Shire Council are working together to assess levee integrity, road safety and identify any impacts to essential services.
It is safe for residents to return to the area. Be aware of hazards that still exist and avoid the flooded area.
What you should do:
  • Drive slowly, obey all roadblocks and never drive through floodwaters. Check the VicTraffic website for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • Stay away from damaged and flooded buildings, fallen or damaged trees and powerlines, and damaged roads until authorities advise they are safe.
  • Many snake bites have been reported. Snakes look for shelter and food in flooded areas. Be careful when returning to houses and sheds near floodwater.
  • A community newsletter has been developed to assist with any questions locals may have. Go to: Community Newsletter - Gannawarra Shire.
If your home or business has been flooded:
  • Contact Gannawarra Shire Council or go to www.emergency.vic.gov.au/relief for relief and recovery information.
  • Check for building damage before you enter.
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible.
  • Protect your health and safety when cleaning. Wear strong boots, gloves and protective clothing and wash your hands and clothes regularly.
  • If you have lost power for a prolonged time due to flooding, you should not consume food from your fridge or freezer. Throw out food that has touched floodwater or has an unusual smell, colour or texture, do not taste or cook it.
  • Electricity: Only turn on power at the mains if water has not entered your property. Have wiring and appliances tested and tagged before use.
  • Gas: If your home has been impacted by floodwater, do not attempt to turn the gas supply back on. Gas lines may contain water and must be checked by the distribution company. Contact details can be found on the top right of your gas bill.
Infectious diseases:
Floodwater can contain sewage and other waste which can cause infections or diseases. To reduce your risk of illness:
  • Never use floodwater or water that may not be safe to wash dishes, brush your teeth, wash your hands, wash and prepare food, make ice or make baby formula.
  • Always wash your hands with soap and safe water when preparing and eating food, after clean-up activities and after touching items wet or damaged by floodwater or sewage.
  • If you have an open cut or sore, keep it clean with soap and cover with waterproof dressings. Speak to a doctor for advice if it has been exposed to floodwater or mud. 
  • Seek medical attention if you have any symptoms of gastro, flu-like symptoms, or if any wounds become red and infected. Find out more: www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/emergencies-floods
Mould:
  • Flooding, excess moisture and pooled water can cause mould growth in your home. When returning to your home after a flood, be aware of any visible mould or a musty smell. High mould levels are likely if the house has been flooded for more than two days. Seek advice from your insurance company before you start to clean-up, including the disposal of water or mould-damaged items.
  • If you decide to remove the mould yourself, make sure there is good ventilation and wear protective clothing such as a shower cap, rubber gloves, eye protection, overalls, suitable footwear and a P1 or P2 face mask (available from your hardware store).
  • For information on how to clean up and remove mould, visit www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/conditionsandtreatments/mould-removal-at-home
Flood-affected septic systems:
If your property has been affected by floodwater, a licensed plumber should assess your septic system for safety and function. A damaged system could back up into your house or garden. Parts of the system that may be damaged include:
  • Shallow PVC pipes that may be blocked
  • Tanks and sumps
  • Disposal/irrigation system and pipework
  • Pumps and equipment with electrical components.
Mosquito alert:
The risk of mosquito breeding is high. You can reduce your risk of being bitten and getting sick:
  •  Wear loose, light-coloured clothes and covered shoes when you are outside
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens
  • Use insecticide sprays indoors and mosquito coils outdoors
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.
  • Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease
Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES call 132 500.

This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This will be the last message issued for the Evacuation of Kerang. Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings on VicEmergency.

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Yarra River from Millgrove to Coldstream.

The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 21 mm in the upper part of the catchment and about 9 mm in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Friday 28 October 2022. Rainfall totals of 5-15 mm are forecast for the catchment for Saturday 29 October 2022

Yarra River from Millgrove to Coldstream:

The level of the Yarra River at Coldstream is currently steady at 5.73 metres, exceeding the Moderate Flood Level (5.10 metres). It is expected to drop below the Moderate Flood Level on Monday morning (31 October 2022), and below the Minor Flood Level (4.0 metres) on Wednesday morning (2 November 2022).

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa.

MODERATE FLOODING CONTINUING AT KIALLA WEST DURING SATURDAY AND INTO SUNDAY

MINOR FLOODING EASING AT EUROA

Rainfall during Friday caused small renewed rises along the Seven Creeks, with minor flooding currently easing at Euroa. Moderate flooding is continuing at Kialla West.

Further rainfall is forecast for the Seven and Castle Creek catchments from Sunday evening which may result in renewed river level rises into next week. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.


Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa
  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa.
  • The Seven Creeks at Kialla West is currently at 5.21 metres and steady, with moderate flooding. The Seven Creeks at Kialla West may remain above the moderate flood level (5.00 m) for the remainder of Saturday and into Sunday.

Updated Community information: 
In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   

To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   

Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.   

If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT!    

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall.  

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do:

Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
Returning home:
  •  Only turn your power on at the main electrical switchboard if water has not entered the property. 
  •  If water has entered your property, do not put the power back on until the property wiring has been tested by a licensed electrician. 
  •  If any appliances have been inundated, do not plug them in or switch them on until they have been tested by a licensed electrician.
  •  For more information visit: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/electrical-emergency/
  • Be aware of any road closures when you return.
Generators
  • If you are using a generator, do not attempt to connect it to the wiring of your home. This is dangerous and illegal.
  •  A generator should only be used outside, with an extension cord to supply power direct to appliances such as the fridge or freezer. 
  • Using a generator indoors creates a number of safety risks including the potential for carbon monoxide poisoning or a fire.   
Recovery:
  •  Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  •  Register for clean up on private property; 
  •  Navigating financial and other support ;
  •  Access to temporary accommodation Mental health and wellbeing support
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
  • If you are using a generator, do not attempt to connect it to the wiring of your home. This is dangerous and illegal.   A generator should only be used outside, with an extension cord to supply power direct to appliances such as the fridge or freezer. Using a generator indoors creates a number of safety risks including the potential for carbon monoxide poisoning or a fire.  
Impacts in your area:

  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding. Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Health Messaging
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other contaminants.  Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home.   
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick.     
  • Flooding can cause sewage to overflow inside your home. Contact with sewage can make people sick, so contaminated areas must be cleaned and disinfected.  
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away including canned and packaged foods.   
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.
Recovery: 
  •  Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: navigating available supports mental health and wellbeing support The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 If your home is flooding and you need emergency assistance Call 000 If your home is about to flood Call VICSES on 132 500
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

WATCH & ACT - RIVERINE FLOOD - Avoid the Flooded Area 
Incident Location: Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa
Issue Date: Saturday 29 October 2022, 01:01 pm
Next Update: Sunday 30 October 2022, 12:00 pm

More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/25400/moreinfo

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa.

MODERATE FLOODING CONTINUING AT KIALLA WEST DURING SATURDAY AND INTO SUNDAY

MINOR FLOODING EASING AT EUROA

Rainfall during Friday caused small renewed rises along the Seven Creeks, with minor flooding currently easing at Euroa. Moderate flooding is continuing at Kialla West.

Further rainfall is forecast for the Seven and Castle Creek catchments from Sunday evening which may result in renewed river level rises into next week. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary. 


Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa
- Moderate flooding is occurring along the Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa.
- The Seven Creeks at Kialla West is currently at 5.21 metres and steady, with moderate flooding. The Seven Creeks at Kialla West may remain above the moderate flood level (5.00 m) for the remainder of Saturday and into Sunday.


Updated Community information: 
In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   

To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   

Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas.  

The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.    

If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT!     

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall.  

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.    

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Traralgon Creek.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON.

A deepening low will approach from the west, expected to be located near western Bass Strait by late Sunday, extending a cold front into western Victoria. 
The low will then dive south of Tasmania on Monday as the front crosses eastern Victoria, followed by another low pressure trough which will cross the state on Tuesday.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for Sunday, Monday and Tuesday.

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall.

Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the watch area from Monday afternoon. Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible from early next week at some locations.

The Bureau of Meteorology is continuing to monitor the situation and will issue catchment specific warnings as required.

Catchment likely to be affected include:

Traralgon Creek
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon and at Seymour.

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM LAKE EILDON SINCE SATURDAY MORNING

MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SEYMOUR SUNDAY MORNING

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT TAGGERTY, SEYMOUR, MURCHISON, SHEPPARTON AND MCCOYS BRIDGE

  • Moderate flooding developed at Downstream Lake Eildon during Saturday morning and may develop along the Goulburn River at Seymour during Sunday morning. 
  • Minor flooding is currently occurring along the Goulburn River catchment at Taggerty, Seymour, Murchison, Shepparton and McCoys Bridge.
  • Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon will be increasing to around 30,000 ML/d from Saturday evening (around 06:00 pm).
  • The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour:
  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour.
  • Minor flooding is occurring at Trawool. 
  • River levels are rising and may reach the moderate flood level during Sunday morning.
  • The Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon is currently at 4.27 metres and steady, with moderate flooding. 
  • The Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon is likely to reach around 4.40 metres Saturday evening and remain steady around that level overnight into Sunday morning.
  • The Goulburn River at Seymour is currently at 4.73 metres and rising, with minor flooding. 
  • The Goulburn River at Seymour is likely to reach the moderate flood level (5.20 m) Sunday morning. 
  • Further rises are possible.
Goulburn River upstream of Lake Eildon:
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River upstream of Lake Eildon at Dohertys, where the river level peaked at 2.33 metres during Saturday morning. 
  • River levels are now falling slowly.
Acheron River:
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Acheron River.
  • The Acheron River at Taggerty peaked around the moderate flood level (2.60 m) overnight Friday into Saturday and is currently at 2.45 metres and falling, with minor flooding. 
  • The Acheron River at Taggerty is likely to remain above the minor flood level (2.30 m) during Saturday and into Sunday.

Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.

If you are planning to camp or go bush driving close to rivers or creeks this long weekend, DON'T!

Unexpected and rapid river and creek levels are very likely even with small amounts of rain and ongoing water releases from Lake Eildon dam.
Your access tracks in and out might be flooded and you might end up stranded for days.

Support the local towns and make sure to set a watch zone for your location this long weekend and regularly check emergency radio broadcasters (ABC or UGFM radio) via your car radio if necessary.

What you should do:

  • Check out the Seymour Local Flood guide or the Mitchell Shire Flood Emergency Plan for more detailed flood information and maps https://www.ses.vic.gov.au/plan-and-stay-safe/flood-guides/mitchell-shire-council
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation. 
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground, if not already done and is safe to.
  • Be prepared to move household items to higher ground, on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes, medications and scripts (prescriptions) with you.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • GMW Water are releasing water from Lake Eildon to control the rate the storage is filling and make room for further inflows.  
  • GMW advises “It is important people who live or farm on floodplains have their properties prepared for any potential flood events. This includes ensuring there are no flaws with any dams on their properties and having a plan to move livestock and equipment to higher ground".
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home and sheds, garages etc is likely to occur in some locations.
  • A small number of properties are likely to be impacted and possibility become isolated.
In Seymour, at the predicted 5.2 m (Moderate flood level): 
  • Tierney, High and Wallis Streets start to flood. 
  • Emily Street stormwater backs up around roads and gardens. 
  • Goulburn River Caravan Park likely to re-activate their evacuation plan
From minor flood level (4.0m), Kings Park, three of the local caravan parks and farmland along the Old Hume Highway start to flood. Seymour stormwater drainage commences overflowing.
  • the Goulburn River breaks its banks causing flooding on low-lying farmland, parkland, low-lying roads and river crossings. 

  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • You may lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
  • Fishing, kayaking, Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 11:50 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Latrobe River Yallourn to Traralgon Creek:

MODERATE FLOODING IS LIKELY AT THOMS BRIDGE FROM SATURDAY AFTERNOON

Minor flooding is occurring across the Latrobe River catchment. Continuing rainfall activity from Monday to Friday caused stream rises across the catchment.

Showers are forecast for the remainder of Saturday, and the situation is being monitored closely.

Latrobe River Yallourn to Traralgon Creek:

Moderate flooding is likely along the Latrobe River Yallourn to Traralgon Creek.

The Latrobe River at Thoms Bridge is currently at 4.63 metres and rising, with minor flooding. The Latrobe River at Thoms Bridge is likely to reach the moderate flood level (5.00 m) Saturday afternoon. The river level may remain above the moderate flood level (5.00 m) overnight Saturday into Sunday.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.

  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.

  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  •  High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides – be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
  • Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall. 

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.    

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Gunbower, Leitchville, Torrumbarry and Patho.

  • The Murray River at Torrumbarry Weir may peak around 7.90 metres during Sunday, with major flooding.
  • The Torrumbarry Weir water level was 7.84 as at 3:00pm on Saturday 29 October.
  • Ongoing maintenance works are continuing to improve the serviceability of the levee with continual monitoring occurring.
The latest community newsletter from Saturday 29 October is available here: Community Newsletter
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off the gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 

If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
  • Lift it. Be prepared to move valuables and household items to higher ground, on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 

Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • You may see animals attempting to move to higher ground, including snakes. Leave all uninjured wildlife alone and they are likely to be fatigued and stressed. If you see animals that appear to e injured or caught in floodwater, call 136 186 or advise via the wildlife emergency app.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 04:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

Minor flooding is occurring at Mongans Bridge, Kiewa Main Stream and Bandiana.

On Saturday morning a minor flood peak was observed at Mongans Bridge, where the Kiewa River is currently easing with minor flooding. A minor flood peak is expected at Kiewa (Main Stream) during Sunday, and minor flooding is expected to continue at Bandiana over the next few days.

In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Saturday, rainfall totals of 10-20 mm were recorded in the Kiewa River catchment. Further rainfall is forecast for the Kiewa River catchment from Sunday evening which may result in renewed river level rises into next week.

Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge:
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge. Renewed rises are likely from early next week with forecast rainfall.
  • The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is currently at 3.39 metres, above the minor flood level (3.30m) and slowly rising. It is likely to peak near 3.45 metres Sunday morning, with minor flooding.
  • The Kiewa River at Bandiana is currently at 2.98 metres, above the minor flood level (2.80 m) and steady. It is likely to remain above the minor flood level (2.80 m) over the next few days.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Loddon River Loddon Weir to Kerang.

Minor to moderate flooding is continuing along the Loddon River. The main flood peak is now approaching Appin South, where moderate flooding is occurring.

  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Loddon River Loddon Weir to Kerang.
  • The Loddon River at Downstream (D/S) Loddon Weir is currently at 5.33m and falling slowly, with minor flooding.
  • The Loddon River at Appin South is currently at 3.15m and rising slowly, with moderate flooding. The Loddon River at Appin South is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (3.10m) for the next few days. The river level may reach around 3.20m overnight Sunday into Monday.
  • The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge fell below the moderate flood level Friday night and is currently at 77.45m Australian Height Datum (AHD) and falling slowly, with minor flooding The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge is expected to remain above the minor flood level (77.00m) for the next few days.
In the 24 hours to 10am Saturday, rainfall totals of up to 5mm were recorded in the upper Loddon River catchment. No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Saturday. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Check you have enough food, drinking water and medications.
  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - do not drive through floodwater. Do not overestimate the capability of your vehicle. It doesn’t take much to make your car become unstable, lose traction or wash away.
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
Community newsletter 
A community newsletter for Gannawarra Shire has been developed to assist with any questions locals may have. Go to: Community Newsletter - Gannawarra Shire.
Impacts in your area:
  • A number of local and arterial roads are closed due to floodwater. For more information on road closures go to VicTraffic. 
  • Some areas are likely to lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
  • Be aware that snakes may look for shelter and food inside houses, storage sheds and other buildings near floodwater. Damaged structures and debris are more accessible to snakes.
Mosquito alert:
The risk of mosquito breeding is high. You can reduce your risk of being bitten and getting sick:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.
  • Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app

Accessibility:

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Yea River.

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM LAKE EILDON SINCE SATURDAY MORNING

MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SEYMOUR SUNDAY MORNING

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT TAGGERTY, SEYMOUR, MURCHISON, SHEPPARTON AND MCCOYS BRIDGE

Moderate flooding developed at Downstream Lake Eildon during Saturday morning and may develop along the Goulburn River at Seymour during Sunday morning. Minor flooding is currently occurring along the Goulburn River catchment at Taggerty, Seymour, Murchison, Shepparton and McCoys Bridge.
Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon will be increasing to around 30,000 ML/d from Saturday evening (around 06:00 pm).
The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Yea River:
River levels along the Yea River are below the minor flood level and steady.

Updated Community information:
In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.  
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.
Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.

If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT! 

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall and ongoing water releases from Lake Eildon.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do:
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one. 
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • If cleaning after damage has occurred, protect your health and safety. 
  • Protect your lungs by wearing a N95 or P2 mask. Wear strong boots, gloves and protective clothing and wash your hands and clothes regularly. 
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. 
  • Don’t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water. Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760
Impacts in your area: 
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Low lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.


This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
Recovery: 
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  • Register for clean up on private property; 
  • Navigating financial and other support 
  • Access to temporary accommodation 
  • Mental health and wellbeing support 
The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit Emergency Recovery Vic for further information. 

For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  • Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away, including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.
Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

ADVICE - RIVERINE FLOOD - Stay Informed
Incident Location: Yea River
Issue Date: Saturday 29 October 2022, 06:01 pm
Next Update: Sunday 30 October 2022, 12:00 pm

More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/25463/moreinfo

This Flood Watch is being issued for Yea River.

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM LAKE EILDON SINCE SATURDAY MORNING

MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SEYMOUR SUNDAY MORNING

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT TAGGERTY, SEYMOUR, MURCHISON, SHEPPARTON AND MCCOYS BRIDGE

Moderate flooding developed at Downstream Lake Eildon during Saturday morning and may develop along the Goulburn River at Seymour during Sunday morning. Minor flooding is currently occurring along the Goulburn River catchment at Taggerty, Seymour, Murchison, Shepparton and McCoys Bridge.
Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon will be increasing to around 30,000 ML/d from Saturday evening (around 06:00 pm).
The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary. 

Yea River:
River levels along the Yea River are below the minor flood level and steady. 

Updated Community information:
In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.  
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.
Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas.  


The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree. 

If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT! 

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall and ongoing water releases from Lake Eildon.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
