properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Lakes Entrance.

  • Due to a whale carcass at the beach, which was first located last week, there could be an increase in shark activity.
  • A whale carcass can attract sharks to the area and mean they are closer to the shore than normal.
  • While it is not uncommon for sharks to be present off the Victorian coast, you should exercise additional caution in the area.
  • The carcass was originally located in Marlo, but as of 21/10/2022, it has broken up and spread out along the coast between Lake Tyers Beach and Lakes Entrance.
  • This is an update, replacing the Advice issued on Monday at 3.15pm.
Avoid the area. Stay informed and do not enter the water at closed beaches.
What you should do:

  • If you see sharks, report the sighting by calling Triple Zero (000) or notify lifesavers immediately if you are at a patrolled beach.
Staying safe at nearby beaches:
  • Always swim, dive or surf with a friend.
  • Swim between the red and yellow flags on patrolled beaches.
  • Don't swim in places where human or animal waste enters the water.
  • Keep away from large schools of fish, seals or other wildlife as these can attract sharks.
Impacts in your area:
  • The Victorian Fisheries Authority is monitoring for shark sightings and providing advice to relevant authorities. 
This message was issued by VFA.

The next update is expected by 02/11/2022 11:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Snowy River downstream of McKillops Bridge.

Minor flooding is continuing downstream of Basin Ck during Saturday and into Sunday. Minor flooding has eased at Orbost.

In the 24 hours to 3:00 pm Saturday, rainfall totals of less than 5 mm were recorded in the Snowy River catchment. No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Saturday. Further rainfall is forecast from late Sunday which may lead to renewed rises.

The situation will continue to be monitored closely and warnings will be updated if required.

Snowy River downstream of McKillops Bridge:

Minor flooding is occurring along the Snowy River downstream of McKillops Bridge.

The Snowy River D/S Basin Ck is currently at 3.63 metres and falling, with minor flooding. The Snowy River D/S Basin Ck is expected to remain around the minor flood level (3.50 m) during Saturday and into Sunday.

The Snowy River at Orbost is currently at 4.12 metres and slowly falling, below the minor flood level. The Snowy River at Orbost is expected to remain below the minor flood level (4.20 m) during Saturday and into Sunday.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides – be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

Snowy Catchments Campgrounds that are Closed due to Flooding: As of Wednesday 26th October, Long Point, Sandy Point and Wood Point campgrounds are close.

Farmers who have been impacted by flood and requires assistance or have urgent animal welfare needs, please contact AgVic - VicEmergency Hotline on 1800 226 226

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 05:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Minor flooding is occurring along the Avoca River to Charlton Town.

The Avoca River at Charlton Town is currently at 4.13 metres and slowly falling, with minor flooding. The Avoca River at Charlton Town is likely to remain above the minor flood level (4.00m) during Saturday and into Sunday.

In the 24 hours to 12pm Saturday, rainfall totals of less than 5mm were recorded in the Avoca River catchment. No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Saturday, however further rainfall is forecast from late Sunday which may lead to renewed rises.

The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:

Impacts in your area:

Mosquito alert:

  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.
  • Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.

Moderate Flooding has developed at Wangaratta Saturday afternoon.

Moderate flooding is occurring along the King River at Docker Rd Bridge and has extended downstream to Wangaratta during Saturday afternoon. Minor flooding is occurring along the King River at Downstream Lake William Hovell, the Buffalo River at Downstream Lake Buffalo, and the Ovens River at Rocky Point.

No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Saturday and into Sunday.

Forecast rainfall from Sunday evening and for the first few days of next week is likely to see renewed rises throughout the Ovens and King catchments.

Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point
  • The Ovens River at Wangaratta is currently at 12.42 metres and rising, with moderate flooding. It is likely to peak near 12.50 metres overnight Saturday into Sunday.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • A number of local roads and may be closed due to flooding.
At the Minor Flood Level (11.9m):
  • Water up to Yogi's chin in Apex Park
  • Apex Park and farmland along the Ovens, King and possibly the Fifteen Mile Creek floodplains north, south and east of Wangaratta may begin flooding
  • Bike paths and walking tracks around and downstream of Apex Park and the Northern Beaches may be closed
  • Many riverside carparks may be closed including Sydney Beach, Bickerton St and Baker St
  • The Great Alpine Road at East Wangaratta is closed due to flooding, with detours in place

At the Moderate Flood Level (12.4m):
  • Extensive flooding through APEX Park, water up to Yogi's mouth
  • Bickerton St carpark will be closed and the access road to Painters Island Caravan Park flooded
  • Shallow flooding to Pinkerton Cres and backyards along Templeton St and Baker St

The following roads may be affected by flooding as the river level rises and may be closed:
  • The Great Alpine Road, East Wangaratta
  • Peechelba Road (East of the Ovens River)
  • Wilson Road (outside of the levee protected area)
  • Markwood-Everton Road
  • Bickerton Street, including the car parking areas
  • Milawa-Tarrawingee Road
  • College Street, preventing access to the Northern Beaches carpark
  • Markwood-Tarrawingee Road
  • Pinkerton Crescent
  • Baker Street car park
  • Dowling Lane River Road
  • Oxley Flats Road
  • Stamps Lane / Dale Street / Ambrosio Road
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 11:00 am or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Hughes Creek.

Updated Community Information: In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning. 
If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.    If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT!    Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall.  
 Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary

  • MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING  DOWNSTREAM OF LAKE EILDON SINCE SATURDAY MORNING

  • Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon will be increasing to around 30,000 ML/d from Saturday evening (around 06:00 pm).The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.

Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.

The level of the Watts River at Healesville is currently steady at 3.10 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (2.80 metres). It is expected to drop below the Minor Flood Level overnight Saturday (29 October 2022).

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.location: Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham
properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham. 

Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham:

  • Major flooding is occurring at Echuca, Moama, Torrumbarry and Barham.
  • The Murray River at Echuca peaked at 94.98 metres AHD around 11:45 pm Wednesday and is currently at 94.87 metres AHD and falling slowly, with major flooding. 
  • The Murray River at Echuca may remain above the major flood level (94.40 metres AHD) until 05-06 November.
  • The Murray River at Torrumbarry Weir may peak around 7.90 metres during Sunday, with major flooding.
  • The Murray River at Barham is currently at 6.18 metres and falling slowly, with major flooding. 
  • The Murray River at Barham may remain above the major flood level (6.10 metres) until 10-12 November.
Torrumbarry to Leitchville
  • A Watch and Act - Move to Higher Ground message is in place for Torrumbarry, Patho, Gunbower and Leitchville. 
  • Ongoing maintenance works are continuing to improve the serviceability of the levee with continual monitoring occurring. 
Wharparilla
  • Watch and Act - Move to Higher Ground messages are in place for O'Dwyer Road and Wharparilla-Glyn Road.
There are Evacuation Warnings in place for 
  • Echuca and Echuca Village, and 
  • Barmah and Lower Moira. 
The latest community newsletter from Saturday 29 October is available here: Community Newsletter
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater. 
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary.
  • For commercial and recreational users of the Murray River: NSW State Emergency Services have declared an emergency area on the Murray River for areas downstream of Tocumal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge under the state Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act). Do not enter the emergency area. This applies to all commercial and recreational users. Visit the NSW SES website for information: https://www.ses.nsw.gov.au/news/all-news/2022/emergency-area-declared-murray-river/
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria.
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.   
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
  • Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • You may see animals attempting to move to higher ground, including snakes.
  • Leave all uninjured wildlife alone as they are likely to be fatigued and stressed.
  • If you see animals that appear injured or caught in flood water, call 136186 or via the Wildlife Emergency App
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 05:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for South Gippsland Rivers.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON.

A deepening low will approach from the west, expected to be located near western Bass Strait by late Sunday, extending a cold front into western Victoria. The low will then dive south of Tasmania on Monday as the front crosses eastern Victoria, followed by another low pressure trough which will cross the state on Tuesday.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for Sunday, Monday and Tuesday

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall.

Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the watch area from Monday afternoon. Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible from early next week at some locations.

The Bureau of Meteorology is continuing to monitor the situation and will issue catchment specific warnings as required.

Catchment likely to be affected include:

South Gippsland Rivers
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM LAKE EILDON SINCE SATURDAY MORNING

MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SEYMOUR SUNDAY MORNING

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT TAGGERTY, SEYMOUR, MURCHISON, SHEPPARTON AND MCCOYS BRIDGE

Moderate flooding developed at Downstream Lake Eildon during Saturday morning and may develop along the Goulburn River at Seymour during Sunday morning. Minor flooding is currently occurring along the Goulburn River catchment at Taggerty, Seymour, Murchison, Shepparton and McCoys Bridge.
Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon will be increasing to around 30,000 ML/d from Saturday evening (around 06:00 pm).
The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
  
Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton:  
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.
  • The Goulburn River at Murchison is currently at 9.13 metres and rising, with minor flooding. Small additional rises are possible and the Goulburn River at Murchison may reach around 9.30 metres overnight Saturday into Sunday.
  • The Goulburn River at Shepparton is currently at 10.46 metres and falling, with minor flooding. The Goulburn River at Shepparton is expected to remain above the minor flood level (9.50 m) during Saturday and into Sunday.
  • Please note that Regional Roads Victoria have advised that the Murchison Bridge on the Murchison-Violet Town Road (High Road) is open to light vehicles only. NO TRUCKS OR HEAVY AGRICULTURE MACHINERY.  

Updated Community Information: 
In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   
Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 

The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.   

If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT!    

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall and ongoing water releases from Lake Eildon.   

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Don't go fishing, kayaking, or boating. Floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
  • If cleaning after damage has occurred, protect your health and safety.
  • Protect your lungs by wearing a N95 or P2 mask. 
  • Wear strong boots, gloves and protective clothing and wash your hands and clothes regularly. 
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Don’t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water. 
  • Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760
If returning home
  • Only turn your power on at the main electrical switchboard if water has not entered the property. 
  • If water has entered your property, do not put the power back on until the property wiring has been tested by a licensed electrician. 
  • If any appliances have been inundated, do not plug them in or switch them on until they have been tested by a licensed electrician. 
  • For more information visit: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/electrical-emergency/
Impacts in your area: 

  • Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Don’t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water. 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Please note that Regional Roads Victoria have advised that the Murchison Bridge on the Murchison-Violet Town Road (High Road) is open to light vehicles only. NO TRUCKS OR HEAVY AGRICULTURE MACHINERY. 
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Don't go fishing, kayaking, or boating. Floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.  
Recovery:
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with:
  • Register for clean up on private property; 
  • Navigating financial and other support
  • Access to temporary accommodation 
  • Mental health and wellbeing support 
The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit www.erv.vic.gov.au for further information. 

For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. 
For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Health Messaging
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  • Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away, including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.
Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Advice is being issued in the lower Bendigo and Bullock Creeks.

  • Flooding is occurring in the lower Bendigo and Bullock Creeks. 
  • Increased flows from Kow Swamp into Pyramid Creek continue to create significant impacts for downstream areas. Flood waters may continue to impact properties along the Pyramid Creek from Kow Swamp to Kerang over the coming days.
  • Residents in properties along the Pyramid Creek from Kow Swamp to Kerang should expect to see increased water levels below Milnes Bridge and further to the Kerang-Koondrook Road, with some levees being overtopped leading to potential breaches.
  • A deepening low will approach from the west on Sunday, expected to be located near western Bass Strait by evening with a cold front extending into western Victoria, followed by another low pressure trough which will cross the state on Tuesday.
  • Widespread showers and storms are expected for Sunday, Monday and Tuesday. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • People living or working along rivers and streams must monitor the latest weather forecasts and warnings and be ready to move to higher ground should flooding develop.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.

Mosquito alert:
The risk of mosquito breeding is high. You can reduce your risk of being bitten and getting sick:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.
  • Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease
Impacts in your area
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home may occur in some locations.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Check the VicTraffic website for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service 

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 05:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.location: Yarra River from Coldstream to Warrandyte
properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Yarra River from Coldstream to Warrandyte.

The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 21 mm in the upper part of the catchment and about 9 mm in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Friday 28 October 2022. Rainfall totals of 5-15 mm are forecast for the catchment for Saturday 29 October 2022

Yarra River from Coldstream to Warrandyte:

The level of the Yarra River at Yarra Glen is currently steady at 4.73 metres, exceeding the Moderate Flood Level (4.60 metres). It is expected to drop below the Moderate Flood Level on Monday morning (31 October 2022), and below the Minor flood Level (4.1 metres) on Wednesday evening (2 November 2022).

The level of the Yarra River at Christmas Hills is currently steady at its peak of 3.96 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres).

The level of the Yarra River at Warrandyte is currently at 4.09 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres ), and rising. It is expected to peak around 4.2 metres overnight Saturday (29 October 2022). This is the highest flood level since the August 1996 flood (4.29 metres).

Minor to Moderate flooding in the Yarra/Watts River catchment is causing substantial inundation in the rural and/or urban areas, and disruption to traffic. Melba Highway at Yarra Glen is expected to get flooded.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.

Roads that may be impacted by flooding of the Yarra River in Yarra Glen include: 
  • The Healesville-Yarra Glen road, between Bell Street and Yarra Valley Racecourse and between the Melba Highway and the Yarra Glen Bypass. 
  • Armstrong Grove 
  • Bell Street 
  • Yarraview Road
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 09:30 am or as the situation changes.

  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Campaspe River downstream of Rochester. 
  • The Campaspe River at Echuca is currently at 94.57 m AHD and steady, with moderate flooding. The river is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (94.40 m AHD) for the remainder of Saturday and into Sunday. 
  • River levels will remain elevated due to flood waters backing up from the Murray River and are expected to continue in the coming days.

  • A deepening low will approach from the west, expected to be located near western Bass Strait by late Sunday, extending a cold front into western Victoria. The low will then dive south of Tasmania on Monday as the front crosses eastern Victoria.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Wharparilla.

Flooding has impacted residents in the area of O'Dwyer Road, Wharparilla. 

Flooding is expected to remain at current levels for the next week.

The latest Community Newsletter from Saturday 29 October is available here: Community Newsletter
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au

properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Castle Creek.

MODERATE FLOODING CONTINUING AT KIALLA WEST DURING SATURDAY AND INTO SUNDAY
MINOR FLOODING EASING AT EUROA

Rainfall during Friday caused small renewed rises along the Seven Creeks, with minor flooding currently easing at Euroa. Moderate flooding is continuing at Kialla West.
Further rainfall is forecast for the Seven and Castle Creek catchments from Sunday evening which may result in renewed river level rises into next week. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Castle Creek:
River levels are easing along the Castle Creek and expected to remain below the minor flood level at Telfords Bridge over the remainder of the weekend.

Updated Community information:
In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   

To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   

Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.   

If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT!    

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • For more information on road closures go to traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
Recovery: 
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  • Register for clean up on private property; 
  • Navigating financial and other support 
  • Access to temporary accommodation 
  • Mental health and wellbeing support 

The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit www.erv.vic.gov.au for further information. 

For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. 
For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  • Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away, including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.

Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Yarra River from Warrandyte to Abbotsford.

The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 21 mm in the upper part of the catchment and about 9 mm in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Friday 28 October 2022. Rainfall totals of 5-15 mm are forecast for the catchment for Saturday 29 October 2022.

Yarra River from Warrandyte to Abbotsford:

The level of the Yarra River at Templestowe is currently at 5.05 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (3.50 metres), and rising. It is expected to peak around 5.2 metres on Sunday morning (30 October 2022).

The level of the Yarra River at Heidelberg is currently at 8.06 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (6.00 metres), and rising. It is expected to peak around 8.2 metres, just below the Moderate Flood Level (8.30 metres), on Sunday morning (30 October 2022).

The level of the Yarra River at Alphington is currently at 4.52 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres), and rising. It is expected to peak around 4.9 metres, below the Moderate Flood Level (6.00 metres), on Sunday afternoon (30 October 2022).

The level of the Yarra River at Abbotsford is currently at 4.47 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (2.70 metres), and rising. It is expected to peak around 4.9 metres, below the Moderate Flood Level (6.70 metres), on Sunday afternoon (30 October 2022).

Minor to Moderate flooding in the Yarra/Watts River catchment is causing substantial inundation in the rural and/or urban areas, and disruption to traffic. Melba Highway at Yarra Glen is expected to get flooded.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • Minor flooding in the Yarra River catchment is affecting low-lying areas adjacent to the waterway including bicycle paths.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.

Minor flooding is occurring at Khancoban Pondage and Bringenbrong. Minor flooding is possible at Jingelic Saturday evening.

Minor flooding is occurring along the Swampy Plains River at Khancoban Pondage and along the Murray River at Bringenbrong. Minor flooding may develop at Jingellic during Saturday evening, with a peak around the minor flood level possible overnight Saturday into Sunday.

properties.webBody:
This Warning is being issued for Bogong Village and Falls Creek

  • A Landslide has occurred on the Bogong High Plains Road at Bogong Village.
  • There is a large, active, slow moving landslide on the Bogong High Plains Road in the area near Spring Saddle Track above Bogong Village.
  • After recent heavy rainfall, cracking has been identified in the area around Spring Saddle Track and debris has been moving from below the track onto the Bogong High Plains Road.
  • Further rainfall and snow are forecast which could result in imminent failure and pose a threat to life and property. 

  • The Bogong-High Plains Road is closed from Mount Beauty to all traffic - until further notice, and will not reopen until deemed safe.

  • An Exclusion Zone has been established, prohibiting entry into the area defined in the map which is available at https://bit.ly/3gOXZb7. Access to this area is strictly prohibited and is a threat to life if you enter.

This is an update, replacing the warning issued at 2:54 PM, Friday 28/10/2022.
Avoid the area. Stay clear of fallen earth and trees and blocked or damaged roads. Be aware of other hazards caused by the landslide. Do not enter the exclusion zone.

Visitors are advised not to travel to Falls Creek over the Melbourne Cup weekend due to forecast severe weather and snow conditions.
What you should do:
  • If you have chosen to remain, please monitor the road conditions. 
  • If another landslide occurs, act quickly.
  • If you are outside when a landslide occurs, move quickly and keep clear of embankments, trees, power lines and poles.
  • If you are inside, move to the part of building that is furthest away from the approaching landslide and take shelter under a table or bench.
  • Stay away from the impacted area to allow emergency services to help affected communities.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters  and monitoring warnings.

Travelling:
  • Plan your trip in advance - travel may take longer due to closed roads and poor driving conditions.
  • Visitors are advised not to travel to Falls Creek over the Melbourne Cup weekend due to forecast severe weather and snow conditions.
  • There will be no public access to Falls Creek and Bogong Village as the Bogong High Plains Road will remain closed until deemed safe.
  • The Bogong High Plains Road, south of Falls Creek is open to local traffic only, accessible via the Omeo Highway.
Impacts in your area:
The landslide has resulted in:
  • Fallen trees and branches.
  • Dangerous road conditions.
  • Mud and debris on the road.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 31/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Seven Creeks to Euroa

MODERATE FLOODING CONTINUING AT KIALLA WEST DURING SATURDAY AND INTO SUNDAY

MINOR FLOODING EASING AT EUROA

Rainfall during Friday caused small renewed rises along the Seven Creeks, with minor flooding currently easing at Euroa. Moderate flooding is continuing at Kialla West.

Further rainfall is forecast for the Seven and Castle Creek catchments from Sunday evening which may result in renewed river level rises into next week. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Seven Creeks to Euroa
Minor flooding is easing along the Seven Creeks to Euroa.

After a renewed peak near 3.25 metres late Friday evening, the Seven Creeks at Euroa is currently at 3.10 metres and falling, with minor flooding. The Seven Creeks at Euroa is likely to remain above the minor flood level (2.50 m) until Sunday morning.

Updated Community information: 
In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   

To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   

Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.   

If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT!    

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall.   

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
When returning home 
  • Only turn your power on at the main electrical switchboard if water has not entered the property.  
  • If water has entered your property, do not put the power back on until the property wiring has been tested by a licensed electrician.  
  • If any appliances have been inundated, do not plug them in or switch them on until they have been tested by a licensed electrician.  
  • For more information visit: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/electrical-emergency/ 
  • If cleaning after damage has occurred, protect your health and safety. 
  • Protect your lungs by wearing a N95 or P2 mask.  
  • Wear strong boots, gloves and protective clothing and wash your hands and clothes regularly.  
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Don’t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.  
  • Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760

Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and flooding may still affect areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Local roads may still be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Low lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.

This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.  
Recovery: 
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  • Register for clean up on private property; 
  • Navigating financial and other support 
  • Access to temporary accommodation 
  • Mental health and wellbeing support 
The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit www.erv.vic.gov.au for further information. 

For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. 
For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  • Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away, including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.

Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

properties.location: Murray River downstream of Barham to Wentworth
properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Barham to Wentworth.

Floodwaters from the Campaspe and Goulburn Rivers combined with flows down the Murray River have caused major flooding at Echuca where the river level peaked around 94.98m AHD Wednesday night, higher than the October 1993 and November 1975 flood peaks.

As this flood peak extends downstream, major flooding is possible on the Murray River at Swan Hill and moderate flooding may occur at Mildura. Minor flooding is occurring at Boundary Bend, with moderate flooding possible.

  • The Murray River at Swan Hill is likely to exceed the minor flood level (4.50m) late Saturday into Sunday. The river may reach the major flood level (4.70m) during the second week of November (8 to 11 November).
  • The Murray River at Wakool Junction may reach around 11.40m around 20 to 23 November, with moderate flooding.
  • The Murray River at Boundary Bend may exceed the moderate flood level (8.50m) late Saturday into Sunday. The river level may reach around 8.70m around 24 to 26 November, with moderate flooding.
  • The Murray River at Euston may exceed the minor flood level (9.10m) in mid-November. The river level may reach around 9.50m between 25 and 27 November, with minor flooding.
  • The Murray River at Mildura Weir may exceed the minor flood level (36.00mAHD) around 10 to 12 November. The river level may reach 37.50m AHD round the end of November, with moderate flooding, similar to the 1993 flood.
Community updates
Could you spare an hour or two to help fill pallets of sandbags from 9.30am tomorrow (Sunday) at the Lake Boga Community Centre?
  • These filled sandbags are being laid by the thousand each day with the support of our friends from the ADF, and we need to keep up the supply to them so they can continue their great work.
  • Please bring a shovel if you can, high visibility clothing (vest or shirt) and wear secure footwear (steel cap boots preferred).
  • There will be a BBQ after the community meeting to say 'thank you' to all who turned out to help.
Community meetings are being held tomorrow (Sunday) for residents of Lake Boga, Nyah, Tyntynder, Beverford and surrounding local areas:
  • 12pm - Lake Boga Community Centre
  • 2pm - Community Centre, Nyah Recreation Reserve
  • 3.30pm - Beverford School.
An updated Community Newsletter is available that has answers to some of your questions from Monday night's community meeting at Swan Hill, information about how to report levee issues and a link to the online interactive map, which shows the estimated 1993 flood extent.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels online by visiting www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings website.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - do not drive through floodwater. Do not overestimate the capability of your vehicle. It doesn’t take much to make your car become unstable, lose traction or wash away.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Forecasts for Swan Hill and downstream will be progressively refined once the upstream flood peaks along the Murray River and its tributaries are observed.
  • Further rainfall is forecast during Monday and Tuesday, which may cause renewed river level rises and flooding. The situation is being closely monitored and revised predictions will be provided if necessary.
  • High river levels may cause flooding in areas close to rivers and streams and local roads may be closed.
  • Some agricultural land may be vulnerable to flooding. Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area please check https://www.ses.nsw.gov.au/ in New South Wales and https://www.emergency.vic.gov.au/ in Victoria.
Murray River closure:
The Murray River is closed to river craft downstream of Tocumwal Bridge to Robinvale. People and boats are prohibited from entering the river between these locations. Any person on the Murray between these points are to leave the river. This declaration applies to all residents on both sides of the border. Neither NSW or Victorian users are permitted on the river at this time.

Blackwater and blue green algae:  
Significant rainfall and flooding can cause water quality issues like low-oxygen (hypoxic) blackwater and blue green algae. High levels of organic matter have been washed into waterways and, combined with warm weather, can cause oxygen levels in the water to drop. This can harm or cause the death of fish and crayfish. River managers and scientists monitor rivers for water quality issues and work to reduce the impacts of a blackwater event where they can. Low levels of dissolved oxygen are recorded at several locations across northern Victoria and in the Murray River. The scale of the current flooding means water quality will not improve quickly. Any fish death event in Victoria should be reported to the EPA by calling 1300 372 842.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 05:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Saturday, rainfall totals of 10-20 mm were recorded in the Kiewa River catchment. Further rainfall is forecast for the Kiewa River catchment from Sunday evening which may result in renewed river level rises into next week.

Kiewa River to Mongans Bridge 
- Minor flooding is occurring at Mongans Bridge. 
- The Kiewa River at Mongans Bridge is currently 2.62 metres and falling, with minor flooding. 
- Renewed rises are likely from early next week with forecast rainfall. 


Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

This is a Final Minor Flood Warning for the Dandenong Creek. 

The Dandenong Creek catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 15 mm since 09:00 AM Friday 28 October 2022. Rainfall total of less than 5 mm is forecast for the catchment for Saturday 29 October 2022.

The level of the Dandenong Creek at Rowville (Police Road RB) is currently at 4.13 metres, below the Minor Flood Level (4.60 metres) and falling. The River level peaked at 4.44 metres, below the Minor Flood Level around 6:00 AM on Friday morning (28 October 2022).
The threat of flooding is reduced. Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and beware of hazards remaining in the warning area.
What you should do:

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

If your home or business has been flooded:
  • Check for building damage before you enter.
  • Have all electrical and gas equipment professionally tested before use.
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible.

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Damage to roads and buildings caused by flooding may still exist in your area.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This will be the last warning for this flood. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed:

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River upstream of Lake Eildon.

Updated Community Information: 
In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.    If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT!    Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall.  
 Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
  • MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING DOWNSTREAM OF LAKE EILDON SINCE SATURDAY MORNING
  • MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SEYMOUR SUNDAY MORNINGMINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT TAGGERTY, SEYMOUR, MURCHISON, SHEPPARTON AND MCCOYS BRIDGE
  • Moderate flooding developed Downstream of Lake Eildon during Saturday morning and may develop along the Goulburn River at Seymour during Sunday morning. Minor flooding is currently occurring along the Goulburn River catchment at Taggerty, Seymour, Murchison, Shepparton and McCoys Bridge
  • .Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon will be increasing to around 30,000 ML/d from Saturday evening (around 06:00 pm).The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
  • Goulburn River upstream of Lake Eildon:
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River upstream of Lake Eildon at Dohertys, where the river level peaked at 2.33 metres during Saturday morning. River levels are now falling slowly.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 12:50 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away, including canned and packaged foods. It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton

Updated Community information:

1. Illegal levees
In response to a number of concerns raised by community members, landowners are reminded that construction of works to divert the overland flow of water requires approval. To construct levees that interfere with overland water flows, without obtaining approval, is likely to impact on others and is also likely to be deemed illegal. 

We acknowledge these are difficult times for each impacted member of the community however, it is not appropriate to interfere with the natural overland flow of water as it can negatively impact on others. 


2. In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.  
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING DOWNSTREAM OF LAKE EILDON SINCE SATURDAY MORNING
MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SEYMOUR SUNDAY MORNING
MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT TAGGERTY, SEYMOUR, MURCHISON, SHEPPARTON AND MCCOYS BRIDGE
Moderate flooding developed Downstream of Lake Eildon during Saturday morning and may develop along the Goulburn River at Seymour during Sunday morning. Minor flooding is currently occurring along the Goulburn River catchment at Taggerty, Seymour, Murchison, Shepparton and McCoys Bridge.
Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon will be increasing to around 30,000 ML/d from Saturday evening (around 06:00 pm).The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
  • is currently at 10.51 metres and falling, with minor flooding.  The Goulburn River at Shepparton is expected to remain above the minor flood level (9.50 m) during Saturday and into Sunday.  
Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton:
Minor flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton.
The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is currently at 9.91 metres and steady, with minor flooding. The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is expected to remain above the minor flood level (9.00 m) during Saturday and Sunday. 
  •  Please note The Murray Valley Highway is fully closed at Mc Coys Bridge due to Bridge damage. 
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton.  
  • The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is currently at 9.93 metres and steady, below the moderate flood level (10.00 m).   
  • The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is expected to remain above the minor flood level (9.00 m) during Saturday and Sunday.



Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

If you are planning to camp or go bush driving close to rivers or creeks this long weekend, DON'T!   

Unexpected river and creek levels are very likely even with small amounts of rain.   Support the local towns and make sure to set a watch zone for your location this long weekend and regularly check emergency radio broadcasters ( eg ABC radio) via your car radio if necessary.

Be aware of the increased likelihood of trees falling due to the very wet ground, especially in windy conditions. Never shelter under trees.    

Don't go fishing, kayaking, or boating. Floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater
  • In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted area
  •  Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Don’t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water. Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
When returning home:
  • Only turn your power on at the main electrical switchboard if water has not entered the property. 
  •  If water has entered your property, do not put the power back on until the property wiring has been tested by a licensed electrician.  
  •  If any appliances have been inundated, do not plug them in or switch them on until they have been tested by a licensed electrician.  
  •  For more information visit: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/electrical-emergency/ Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
  •  Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • If cleaning after damage has occurred, protect your health and safety. 
  • Protect your lungs by wearing a N95 or P2 mask. 
  • Wear strong boots, gloves and protective clothing and wash your hands and clothes regularly.
  •  Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Don’t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
  •  Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760
Generators

If you are using a generator, do not attempt to connect it to the wiring of your home. This is dangerous and illegal.

A generator should only be used outside, with an extension cord to supply power direct to appliances such as the fridge or freezer. Using a generator indoors creates a number of safety risks including the potential for carbon monoxide poisoning or a fire. 
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Many local roads may still be closed and low bridges may still be underwater.
  • The Murray Valley Highway is fully closed at Mc Coys Bridge due to Bridge damage.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Don't go fishing, kayaking, or boating. Floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 12:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.  
Recovery: 
 Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: Register for clean up on private property; Navigating financial and other support Access to temporary accommodation Mental health and wellbeing support The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit www.erv.vic.gov.au for further information. For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home. 
  • Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  •  Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  •  Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  •  Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  •  Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  •  Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  •  Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away   including canned and packaged foods. 
  •  It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.

Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077. This is a community message to advise the community not to build own levees as it changes the flow of the water and impacting other properties.
